Tough Cookie is one of my favorite holiday books about finding out where you belong or what makes each person unique! I created a fun bulletin board or door decoration kit for your classroom! After reading the book, Tough Cookie, have student explain why they are a tough cookie on their cookie! Stick it on the wall or door of your choice and you have a great representation of each of your students! Ready for an easy craft to do with your kids leading up to break?! All you need is some paper, a white crayon, and some water colors! We are making cards over here, but use your crayon to draw a snowscape. It is almost like a surprise picture because it’s so hard to see the white marks! Then use a color of your choice to paint over the drawing. The white will pop under the water color! 💥 these could be done for cards, art projects, or just killing some time the last week of school!

If you’re looking for something fun and easy for the next two months (or year), try a whole class blackout writing! Spend 10 to 20 minutes on a new prompt each day! Kiddos can write it down in their writing notebooks, a Google document, or a blank paper! I like to print it poster size and have the kiddos color it theme sleeves!

social_posts.post_text: If you haven’t already, check out the book Snowman All Year! Try having your kiddos complete a directed drawing of a snowman and then have them fill in the background or add details if their snowman could hang out all year! Think Olaf vibes! :) have fun!

The perfect activity to complete the last week before break! @2ndgradesassypants and @cootiesandcuties have many different versions of Unlock! This one was perfect to end our week last year and to control the chaos! I would totally recommend!

I know going back to school after break is ROUGH. But I have a little challenge that can make a difference in your classroom and it only takes two minutes a day. 

The 2x10 strategy is so easy to do but can make a big impact! Taking time during transitions, packing up, independent reading, recess, and other times during the day to get to know a specific student is a great relationship building activity. This is especially beneficial for your at risk students. 

Give it a shot! It’s only two minutes but it could make all the difference to one student. ❤️

#teachersfollowteachers #teach #iteach #teacher #teachertiptuesday #teachersofinstagram #teachersofinsta

If you have early learners (my son 🥰) I have an easy counting on game for you! All you need is a deck of cards and some dice. Make sure to remove your face cards before you begin. Have a student draw one card. Then, they will roll. What ever number they roll, they will count on from their drawn card. For example, if I drew a seven and rolled a four, I would count 8, 9, 10, 11. 

You can do this with small groups, one on one, as a class under the projector, or even turn it into a war game with partners! I hope you find this helpful! ❤️

#mathgames #earlylearning #math #teacher #teachersofinstagram #teachersofinsta #teachergram #teachersfollowteachers

Just a thought…. When I am having a rough day, I tell my students right away. I tell them when my kid is sick, I didn’t sleep, I feel overwhelmed, when we lost our dog. I think it is important to model vulnerability so they see that it’s okay. That it’s normal. Feelings are normal. Needing grace is normal. ❤️❤️ Have a beautiful day everyone!

I Spy… but make it math! You can truly a use any operation while playing this game. 
Have students partner up.
-Lay out the cards and have kiddos come up with an equation in their head or on their whiteboard with an answer. 
- Student will say to their partner “I spy 20.”
- Their partner will then have to find the cards that equal 20. 
You can use addition, multiplication, subtraction, and even division if you students use multiple operations!

If you’re looking for a fun way to start your Monday, try this simple activity! Have each kiddo write a multiple choice question about themselves on a whiteboard! It  could be about their weekend, their favorite book, a new game they recently played, or whatever is interesting to them! 

Then, go around and have the kiddos share theirs with others in the classroom. This gets them up, moving, and sharing! It’s a great way to start the week!

Monday Thoughts: I used to be so dead set on teaching specific lessons on empathy. While they are helpful, modeling empathy in front of your students is what will make the difference. 

-listen
-be understanding
-show flexibility 
-be open minded 
-ask questions

If your students or children see you doing these things, they most likely will pick them up as well! Have a great Monday! 💕

Valentine’s Day should not be just about loving someone else, but ourselves too! Here is an easy was to promote self love in the classroom this Valentine’s Day! Give every student a piece of paper and scissors. Have them cut out a heart and write down positive adjectives that describe themselves with their name in the middle. After they have finished, hang them up in the room or have the kiddos take them home!

Today’s game is all about *mixed numbers* and *improper fractions*. You need three to four dice (colored are optional), a whiteboard, and a marker. Students will get lots of repetition turning improper fractions into mixed numbers. This is great for partners and an easy no prep center to throw in your rotations tomorrow!

If you are working on order of operations, I got a game for you! 
You need:
3 (or more dice)
a whiteboard
a marker

Roll the dice and then place parentheses around two of the numbers. You can have students work on any operations you want. Then, have students solve using the order of operations! Super easy and lots of repetition.

These kind of games are great for centers or when you have an extra ten minutes to kill! 

Make sure to like and save if it something you might use in your classroom!

Have you ever used a 💫retrieval grid💫 to start a lesson? It’s a great way to circle back to prior learning and check for understanding! 

Just create 4-6 quick questions about the prior lesson, novel, reading, or topic and have students work on answering them on their own or in small groups. It shouldn’t take any longer then five minutes. This is a great and purposeful way to start each lesson!

With testing right around the corner this is a go to! We talk about the three types of writing we have gone over this school year. Then we create an anchor chart for each type of writing. We look at what’s similar and different with each type. We got this idea from @teachinginroom6 ❤️

I like to give the kiddos multiple prompts during the weeks leading up to the tests and have them do the pre writing work (brainstorm and outline) for each type of writing. If we have time we will do the actually writing as well. I have noticed so many kids just jump straight into the prompt without a plan and then lack organization and focus when it it time to complete the final product. Planning has been 🔑

An oldie but a goodie!! If you’re looking for a fun, collaborative review game check this out! Grab a big piece of butcher paper, pull out your math standards, and create one or two problems per standard. Then put your class in groups. Have kids solve whatever problem they want all together on their whiteboards and then one person per group  fills in the answer in their team color! 

Pro tip: laminate it so you don’t have to make it again next year! 🤣🤡
